<chapter xml:id="chapter-trees" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
<title>Trees and searches</title>

<section xml:id="section-trees-motivation">
<title>Motivation</title>

<example>
	<title>Reducing redundancy</title>
	<p>
	You have set up your own tree-fort communication system out of tin cans and strings.
	(See <xref ref="wexample-paths-treefort-commnet" />.)
	However, peace has broken out and your communication system is underused.
	To address the crippling tin-can-and-string stilts shortage,
	you want to dismantle as much of your network as possible without disrupting communications.
	</p>
	<figure xml:id="figure-trees-comm-network-full">
		<caption>TreeFort CommNet.</caption>
		<image xml:id="image-trees-treefort-commnet-full" width="56.4%">
			<description>A communication network.</description>
			<latex-image><xi:include href="trees.d/treefort-commnet-full.tex" parse="text" /></latex-image>
		</image>
	</figure>
	<p>
	Closed paths are redundant, as communication could be routed around such a path in two directions.
	So try to eliminate closed all paths; two possible solutions appear in <xref ref="figure-trees-comm-network-reduced" />.
	</p>
	<figure xml:id="figure-trees-comm-network-reduced">
		<caption>TreeFort CommNet (after removing redundant communication paths).</caption>
		<sidebyside widths="45% 45%">
			<figure>
				<caption>One possible result of removing redundancy.</caption>
				<image xml:id="image-trees-treefort-commnet-reduced-1" width="56.4%">
					<description>A communication network with redundant paths removed.</description>
					<latex-image><xi:include href="trees.d/treefort-commnet-reduced-1.tex" parse="text" /></latex-image>
				</image>
			</figure>
			<figure>
				<caption>Another possible result of removing redundancy.</caption>
				<image xml:id="image-trees-treefort-commnet-reduced-2" width="56.4%">
					<description>A communication network with redundant paths removed.</description>
					<latex-image><xi:include href="trees.d/treefort-commnet-reduced-2.tex" parse="text" /></latex-image>
				</image>
			</figure>
		</sidebyside>
	</figure>
</example>

<remark><p>
	A more difficult modification of the above example would be to include the length of string in each communication link as a weight for that edge in the graph,
	and then try to determine a configuration that removes the most string from the network without disrupting communications.
</p></remark>

</section>

<section xml:id="section-trees-basics">
<title>Basics</title>

<p><dl width="narrow">
	<li>
		<title>trivial path</title>
		<idx><h>path</h><h>trivial</h></idx>
		<idx><h>graph</h><h>path</h><h>trivial</h></idx>
		<p> a path that consists of a single vertex </p>
	</li>
	<li>
		<title>cycle</title>
		<idx>cycle</idx>
		<idx><h>graph</h><h>cycle</h></idx>
		<p> a closed path </p>
	</li>
	<li>
		<title>proper cycle</title>
		<idx><h>proper</h><h>cycle</h></idx>
		<idx><h>cycle</h><h>proper</h></idx>
		<idx><h>graph</h><h>cycle</h><h>proper</h></idx>
		<p> a nontrivial cycle that is also a trail </p>
	</li>
</dl></p>

<note><p>
	If <m>G</m> contains vertices <m>v,v'</m> and edge <m>e = \{v,v'\}</m>,
	then <m>v,e,v',e,v</m> is a nontrivial cycle which is not proper.
</p></note>

<p><dl width="narrow">
	<li>
		<title>acyclic graph</title>
		<idx>acyclic graph</idx>
		<idx><h>graph</h><h>acyclic</h></idx>
		<p> contains no proper cycles </p>
	</li>
	<li>
		<title>forest</title>
		<idx>forest</idx>
		<idx><h>graph</h><h>forest</h></idx>
		<p> synonym for <term>acyclic graph</term> </p>
	</li>
	<li>
		<title>tree</title>
		<idx>tree</idx>
		<idx><h>graph</h><h>tree</h></idx>
		<p> a connected, acyclic graph </p>
	</li>
</dl></p>

<example>
	<title>A forest of trees</title>
	<p>
	The graph in <xref ref="figure-trees-basic-example" /> is acyclic.
	Each of its connected components is a tree.
	</p>
	<figure xml:id="figure-trees-basic-example">
		<caption>A nonconnected acyclic graph.</caption>
		<image xml:id="image-trees-basic-acyclic" width="43.8%">
			<description>A nonconnected acyclic graph.</description>
			<latex-image><xi:include href="trees.d/basic-acyclic.tex" parse="text" /></latex-image>
		</image>
	</figure>
</example>

<example>
	<title>Decision trees are trees</title>
	<p>
	In <xref ref="wexample-path-num-trails" />, we attempted to determine all possible trails from one node to another in a given graph.
	The graph in <xref ref="figure-paths-mapping-trails" /> that we used to explore possible trails in the given graph is an example of a <term>decision tree</term> <mdash />
	at each node we <q>branched out</q> to new possibilities in continuing the trail.
	As the name suggested, the connected graph we ended up with is a tree.
	</p>
</example>

<proposition xml:id="proposition-trees-forest-subgraphs">
	<title>Subgraphs of forests</title>
	<p><ol>
		<li> Every subgraph of an acyclic graph is acyclic. </li>
		<li xml:id="proposition-trees-forest-subgraphs-connected">
			Every connected subgraph of an acyclic graph is a tree.
			In particular, each connected component of an acyclic graph is a tree.
		</li>
	</ol></p>
</proposition>

</section>

<section xml:id="section-trees-identifying">
<title>Identifying trees</title>

<theorem xml:id="theorem-trees-characterizations">
	<title>Characterizations of trees</title>
	<statement><p>
		The following are equivalent for a graph <m>G = (V,E)</m> with <m>\card{V} = n</m> vertices.
		<ol>
			<li xml:id="theorem-trees-characterizations-tree"> Graph <m>G</m> is a tree. </li>
			<li xml:id="theorem-trees-characterizations-new-edge"> <!-- \label{THEOREM::tree.thms.new.edge} -->
				Graph <m>G</m> is acyclic but the addition of any new edge would create a cycle.
			</li>
			<li xml:id="theorem-trees-characterizations-one-path"> <!-- \label{THEOREM::tree.thms.one.path} -->
				Graph <m>G</m> contains no loops and contains exactly one path between each pair of distinct vertices.
			</li>
			<li xml:id="theorem-trees-characterizations-bridges"> <!-- \label{THEOREM::tree.thms.bridges} -->
				Graph <m>G</m> is connected but every edge of <m>G</m> is a bridge.
			</li>
			<li xml:id="theorem-trees-characterizations-connected-num-edges"> <!-- \label{THEOREM::tree.thms.num.edges} -->
				Graph <m>G</m> is connected and has <em>exactly</em> <m>\card{E} = n-1</m> edges.
			</li>
			<li xml:id="theorem-trees-characterizations-acyclic-num-edges"> <!-- \label{THEOREM::tree.thms.num.edges} -->
				Graph <m>G</m> is acyclic and has <em>exactly</em> <m>\card{E} = n-1</m> edges.
			</li>
		</ol>
	</p></statement>
	<proof>
		<title>
			Proof of the equivalence of
			<xref first="theorem-trees-characterizations-tree" last="theorem-trees-characterizations-bridges" text="local">Statements</xref>
		</title>
		<case>
			<title>
				<xref ref="theorem-trees-characterizations-tree" text="local">Statement</xref>
				implies
				<xref ref="theorem-trees-characterizations-new-edge" text="local">Statement</xref>
			</title>
			<p>
			Suppose <m>G</m> is a tree.
			By definition, it is acyclic.
			Furthermore, suppose we add an edge between vertices <m>v,v'</m>.
			Since trees are connected, there was already a path from <m>v</m> to <m>v'</m> in <m>G</m>.
			Traversing the new edge from <m>v'</m> back to <m>v</m> closes that path to a cycle.
			</p>
		</case>
		<case>
			<title>
				<xref ref="theorem-trees-characterizations-new-edge" text="local">Statement</xref>
				implies
				<xref ref="theorem-trees-characterizations-one-path" text="local">Statement</xref>
			</title>
			<p>
			Considering the contrapositive, we will assume that <xref ref="theorem-trees-characterizations-one-path" text="local">Statement</xref> is false,
			and prove that this implies that <xref ref="theorem-trees-characterizations-new-edge" text="local">Statement</xref> must also be false.
			</p><p>
			For <xref ref="theorem-trees-characterizations-one-path" text="local">Statement</xref> to be false, one of the following must be true.
			<ol marker="(i)">
				<li> Loops exist in <m>G</m>. </li>
				<li> Some pair of distinct vertices in <m>G</m> is not connected. </li>
				<li> Some pair of distinct vertices in <m>G</m> is connected by more than one path. </li>
			</ol>
			In the first case, <m>G</m> would not be acyclic, as a loop is the most basic form of cycle.
			In the second case, adding an edge between these two vertices that were previously unconnected by a path would <em>not</em> create a cycle, as the rest of that cycle other than the new edge would have been a path between the two vertices.
			And in the third case, if a pair of vertices is connected by more than one path then the parts of two such paths that are different could be concatenated (one forward, one reversed) to create a cycle, so that <m>G</m> must be not be acyclic.
			</p><p>
			Thus, in all cases that make
			<xref ref="theorem-trees-characterizations-one-path" text="local">Statement</xref> false,
			<xref ref="theorem-trees-characterizations-new-edge" text="local">Statement</xref> is also false.
			</p>
		</case>
		<case>
			<title>
				<xref ref="theorem-trees-characterizations-one-path" text="local">Statement</xref>
				implies
				<xref ref="theorem-trees-characterizations-bridges" text="local">Statement</xref>
			</title>
			<p>
			Again, we will consider the contrapositive,
			assuming that <xref ref="theorem-trees-characterizations-bridges" text="local">Statement</xref> is false
			and proving that <xref ref="theorem-trees-characterizations-one-path" text="local">Statement</xref> is also false.
			</p><p>
			For <xref ref="theorem-trees-characterizations-bridges" text="local">Statement</xref> to be false, one of the following is true.
			<ol marker="(i)">
				<li> Graph <m>G</m> is not connected. </li>
				<li> Some edge in <m>G</m> is not a bridge. </li>
			</ol>
			In the first case, <m>G</m> must contain at least one pair of vertices that is not connected by <em>any</em> path.
			For the second case, suppose edge <m>e</m> in <m>G</m> is a loop.
			If <m>e</m> is a loop, then <m>G</m> contains loops.
			If <m>e</m> is not a loop, then it is an edge between a pair of distinct vertices, say <m>v</m> and <m>v'</m>.
			But then removing <m>e</m> from <m>G</m> would leave a subgraph <m>G'</m> that still contains both <m>v</m> and <m>v'</m>,
			and which is still connected.
			So this subgraph (and hence <m>G</m>) must contain a path between <m>v</m> and <m>v'</m> that does not involve <m>e</m>.
			On the other hand, <m>v, e, v'</m> is also a path between <m>v</m> and <m>v'</m>.
			So <m>v,v'</m> is a pair of distinct vertices in <m>G</m> for which there is more than one path between them.
			</p><p>
			Thus, in all cases that make
			<xref ref="theorem-trees-characterizations-bridges" text="local">Statement</xref> false,
			<xref ref="theorem-trees-characterizations-one-path" text="local">Statement</xref> is also false.
			</p>
		</case>
		<case>
			<title>
				<xref ref="theorem-trees-characterizations-bridges" text="local">Statement</xref>
				implies
				<xref ref="theorem-trees-characterizations-tree" text="local">Statement</xref>
			</title>
			<p>
			Again, we consider the contrapositive of this logical implication,
			assuming that <xref ref="theorem-trees-characterizations-tree" text="local">Statement</xref> is false
			and proving that <xref ref="theorem-trees-characterizations-bridges" text="local">Statement</xref> is also false.
			However, since both statements contain the substatement that <m>G</m> is connected, we will not negate that part.
			</p><p>
			So assume that <m>G</m> is connected but contains a proper cycle.
			We aim to prove that <em>at least one</em> edge in <m>G</m> is not a bridge.
			In <xref ref="activity-trees-remove-edge-from-contains-a-cycle" />,
			you are asked to prove that none of the edges in the proper cycle that <m>G</m> contains is a bridge, which will complete the proof.
			</p>
		</case>
	</proof>
	<proof>
		<title>
			Proof of the equivalence of
			<xref ref="theorem-trees-characterizations-tree" text="local">Statement</xref>,
			<xref ref="theorem-trees-characterizations-connected-num-edges" text="local">Statement</xref>,
			and
			<xref ref="theorem-trees-characterizations-acyclic-num-edges" text="local">Statement</xref>
		</title>
		<case>
			<title>
				<xref ref="theorem-trees-characterizations-tree" text="local">Statement</xref>
				implies
				<xref ref="theorem-trees-characterizations-connected-num-edges" text="local">Statement</xref>
			</title>
			<p>
			Assume that <m>G</m> is a tree.
			Then it is connected.
			To prove that the number of edges is <m>\card{E} = n - 1</m>, we proceed by (strong) induction on <m>n</m>,
			the number of vertices in <m>G</m>.
			</p><p>
			For the base base case of <m>n = 1</m>,
			<m>\card{E} = 0</m> is the only possibility, as loops are not allowed in a tree.
			</p><p>
			Now the induction step.
			Assume that every tree with <m>k \lt n</m> vertices has <m>k - 1</m> edges.
			Choose some edge in <m>G</m>.
			By <xref ref="theorem-trees-characterizations-bridges" text="local">Statement</xref>,
			removing that edge creates two connected components, <m>G_1</m> and <m>G_2</m>.
			As <m>G</m> is acyclic, these connected components are both trees
			(<xref ref="proposition-trees-forest-subgraphs-connected" text="local">Statement</xref>
			of <xref ref="proposition-trees-forest-subgraphs" />).
			Let <m>k_1, k_2</m> represent the number of vertices in <m>G_1,G_2</m>, respectively,
			so that <m>k_1 + k_2 = n</m>.
			Since each of <m>k_1</m> and <m>k_2</m> must be strictly less than <m>n</m>,
			we may apply our indution hypothesis to each of <m>G_1</m> and <m>G_2</m>,
			so that <m>G_1</m> has exactly <m>k_1 - 1</m> edges and <m>G_2</m> has exactly <m>k_2 - 1</m> edges.
			</p>
			<figure>
				<caption>Tree <m>G</m> splits into subtrees <m>G_1,G_2</m> after removal of an edge.</caption>
				<image xml:id="image-trees-num-edges" width="58.5%">
					<description>A diagram of a tree splitting into two subtrees for an induction argument.</description>
					<latex-image><xi:include href="trees.d/num-edges.tex" parse="text" /></latex-image>
				</image>
			</figure>
			<p>
			Adding up the number of edges in <m>G_1</m> and <m>G_2</m>, along with the single edge in <m>G</m> that was removed to create these two connected components,
			we obtain
			<m> \card{E} = (k_1 - 1) + (k_2 - 1) + 1 = (k_1 + k_2) - 1 = n - 1, </m>
			as desired.
			</p>
		</case>
		<case>
			<title>
				<xref ref="theorem-trees-characterizations-connected-num-edges" text="local">Statement</xref>
				implies
				<xref ref="theorem-trees-characterizations-acyclic-num-edges" text="local">Statement</xref>
			</title>
			<p>
			Consider the contrapositive of this logical implication,
			assuming that <xref ref="theorem-trees-characterizations-acyclic-num-edges" text="local">Statement</xref> is false
			and proving that <xref ref="theorem-trees-characterizations-connected-num-edges" text="local">Statement</xref> is also false.
			However, since both statements contain the substatement that <m>\card{E} = n - 1</m>, we will not negate that part.
			</p><p>
			So assume that <m>G</m> has <m>n - 1</m> edges, but contains a proper cycle.
			We must prove that <m>G</m> cannot be connected in this case.
			Choose an edge <m>e</m> in the proper cycle and create a subgraph <m>G'</m> by removing <m>e</m>.
			Subgraph <m>G'</m> now has <m>n</m> vertices but <m>n - 2</m> edges, and so by the contrapositive of
			<xref ref="theorem-paths-min-edges-connected-graph" /> <m>G'</m> cannot be connected.
			That means that <m>G'</m> contains a pair of vertices <m>v_1,v_2</m> between which no walk exists.
			If there is a walk between <m>v_1,v_2</m> in <m>G</m> but not in <m>G'</m>,
			then that walk must involve the chosen <m>e</m>.
			But then there would be another walk between <m>v_1,v_2</m> in <m>G</m> avoiding <m>e</m> via the rest of the proper cycle containing <m>e</m>.
			And this other walk would be in <m>G'</m> since it does not involve <m>e</m>.
			Except that we assumed there was <em>no</em> walk between <m>v,v'</m> in <m>G'</m>,
			hence there also can be no walk between them in <m>G</m>.
			Thus, <m>G</m> is not connected.
			</p>
		</case>
		<case>
			<title>
				<xref ref="theorem-trees-characterizations-acyclic-num-edges" text="local">Statement</xref>
				implies
				<xref ref="theorem-trees-characterizations-tree" text="local">Statement</xref>
			</title>
			<p>
			Again, consider the contrapositive of this logical implication,
			assuming that <xref ref="theorem-trees-characterizations-tree" text="local">Statement</xref> is false
			and proving that <xref ref="theorem-trees-characterizations-acyclic-num-edges" text="local">Statement</xref> is also false.
			However, since both statements contain the substatement that <m>G</m> is acyclic (part of the definition of <term>tree</term>), we will not negate that part.
			</p><p>
			So assume that <m>G</m> is acyclic but not a tree, <ie /> that <m>G</m> is not connected.
			We must prove that the number of edges in <m>G</m> is different from <m>n - 1</m>, where <m>n</m> is the number of vertices in <m>G</m>.
			Let <m>G_1,G_2,\dotsc,G_\ell</m> be the connected components of <m>G</m>.
			Now, since <m>G</m> is assumed acyclic, each of these connected components is a tree
			(<xref ref="proposition-trees-forest-subgraphs-connected" text="local">Statement</xref>
			of <xref ref="proposition-trees-forest-subgraphs" />).
			We have already proved above that
			<xref ref="theorem-trees-characterizations-tree" text="local">Statement</xref>
			implies
			<xref ref="theorem-trees-characterizations-connected-num-edges" text="local">Statement</xref>,
			so if we write <m>k_i</m> for the number of vertices in component <m>G_i</m>,
			then we may conclude that the number of edges in component <m>G_i</m> is <m>k_i - 1</m>.
			As the components make up the entire graph <m>G</m>,
			we may add up the vertices and edges in each component to get the totals in the full graph:
			<md> n = k_1 + k_2 + \dotsb + k_\ell, </md>
			<md>
				<mrow> \card{E} \amp = (k_1 - 1) + (k_2 - 1) + \dotsb + (k_\ell - 1) </mrow>
				<mrow> \amp = (k_1 + k_2 + \dotsb + k_\ell) - \ell </mrow>
				<mrow> \amp = n - \ell </mrow>
			</md>.
			Since we assume <m>G</m> is not connected, we have <m>\ell \ge 2</m>, and so <m>\card{E} \neq n - 1</m> as desired.
			</p>
		</case>
	</proof>
</theorem>

</section>

<section xml:id="section-trees-depth-breadth-search">
<title>Depth-first and breadth-first searches</title>

<p>
Let <m>G</m> be a graph.
Given vertices <m>v,v'</m> of <m>G</m>,
we might wish to find a path from <m>v</m> to <m>v'</m>, if one exists.
We can do this by constructing a tree <m>T \preceq G</m>.
</p>

<algorithm xml:id="algorithm-trees-depth-first-search">
<!-- \label{ALGO::depth.first} -->
	<title>Depth-first search</title>
	<idx><h>depth-first</h><h>search</h></idx>
	<idx><h>Algorithm</h><h>depth-first search</h></idx>
	<idx><h>graph</h><h>depth-first</h><h>search</h></idx>
	<p>
	To create a tree <m>T</m> that is a subgraph of a graph <m>G</m> wherein a path (in <m>G</m>) from <m>v</m> to <m>v'</m> is evident,
	begin with <m>T</m> containing the single vertex <m>v</m> and no edges.
	Set <m>x=v</m>.
	<ol>
		<li xml:id="algorithm-trees-depth-first-search-look-adjacent">
		<!-- \label{ALGO::depth.first::look.adjacent} -->
			Look for a vertex <m>y</m> of <m>G</m> which is adjacent to <m>x</m> but not already in <m>T</m>.
			If such a <m>y</m> is found, go to
			<xref ref="algorithm-trees-depth-first-search-join-w-edge" text="local">Step</xref>.
			Otherwise, go to
			<xref ref="algorithm-trees-depth-first-search-stop-or-continue" text="local">Step</xref>.
		</li>
		<li xml:id="algorithm-trees-depth-first-search-join-w-edge">
		<!-- \label{ALGO::depth.first::join.w.edge} -->
			Adjoin <m>y</m> and a single edge between <m>x</m> and <m>y</m> to <m>T</m>.
			If <m>y = v'</m>, stop <mdash />
			a path from <m>v</m> to <m>v'</m> exists and is now contained in <m>T</m>.
			Otherwise, set <m>x=y</m> and return to
			<xref ref="algorithm-trees-depth-first-search-look-adjacent" text="local">Step</xref>.
		</li>
		<li xml:id="algorithm-trees-depth-first-search-stop-or-continue">
		<!-- \label{ALGO::depth.first::stop.or.continue} -->
			If you have arrived here immediately after beginning the algorithm
			(<ie /> with <m>x</m> still set to be <m>v</m>),
			stop <mdash /> there is no path from <m>v</m> to <m>v'</m>.
			Otherwise, return to the vertex <m>z</m> adjoined before <m>x</m>.
			Set <m>x = z</m> and return to
			<xref ref="algorithm-trees-depth-first-search-look-adjacent" text="local">Step</xref>.
		</li>
	</ol>
	</p>
</algorithm>

<note><p>
	In <xref ref="algorithm-trees-depth-first-search-look-adjacent" text="local">Step</xref> of the algorithm,
	there is no specification on how to choose a single <m>y</m> satisfying the search criteria from multiple possibilities.
	In other words, there is flexibility in the <term>implementation</term> of the algorithm here,
	and for the problem at hand there may be implementation choices that are more expedient then others.
</p></note>

<example xml:id="example-trees-depth-first-search">
<!-- \label{EXAMPLE::search.trees} -->
	<title>Carrying out a depth-first search</title>
	<p>
	We perform a <xref ref="algorithm-trees-depth-first-search" text="title" />
	on the graph in <xref ref="figure-trees-depth-first-example" />,
	attempting to find a path from vertex <m>1</m> to vertex <m>9</m>.
	In carrying out the algorithm, if we always choose the vertex with the smallest label in
	<xref ref="algorithm-trees-depth-first-search-look-adjacent" text="local">Step</xref>,
	we obtain the graph in <xref ref="figure-trees-depth-first-result-smallest" />.
	The graph in <xref ref="figure-trees-depth-first-result-largest" />
	is the result of always choosing the vertex with the largest label.
	</p>
	<figure xml:id="figure-trees-depth-first-example">
		<caption>An example graph to illustrate depth-first search.</caption>
		<image xml:id="image-trees-depth-first-example" width="52.6%">
			<description>An example graph to illustrate depth-first search.</description>
			<latex-image><xi:include href="trees.d/depth-first-example.tex" parse="text" /></latex-image>
		</image>
	</figure>
	<figure xml:id="figure-trees-depth-first-result">
		<caption>Results of two different implementation choices in a depth-first search.</caption>
		<sbsgroup> <!-- TODO sbsgroup can also take widths ... -->
			<sidebyside width="72.9%"><figure xml:id="figure-trees-depth-first-result-smallest">
				<caption>Result of always choosing to move to the next adjacent vertex of smallest index.</caption>
				<image xml:id="image-trees-depth-first-result-smallest">
					<description>The result tree of depth-first search on an example graph.</description>
					<latex-image><xi:include href="trees.d/depth-first-result-smallest.tex" parse="text" /></latex-image>
				</image>
			</figure></sidebyside>
			<sidebyside width="72.9%"><figure xml:id="figure-trees-depth-first-result-largest">
				<caption>Result of always choosing to move to the next adjacent vertex of largest index.</caption>
				<image xml:id="image-trees-depth-first-result-largest">
					<description>Another result tree of depth-first search on an example graph.</description>
					<latex-image><xi:include href="trees.d/depth-first-result-largest.tex" parse="text" /></latex-image>
				</image>
			</figure></sidebyside>
		</sbsgroup>
	</figure>
</example>

<p>
The depth-first search will not necessarily yield the <em>shortest</em> path from <m>v</m> to <m>v'</m>.
The following algorithm will.
</p>

<algorithm xml:id="algorithm-trees-breadth-first-search">
<!-- \label{ALGO::breadth.first} -->
	<title>Breadth-first search</title>
	<idx><h>breadth-first</h><h>search</h></idx>
	<idx><h>Algorithm</h><h>breadth-first search</h></idx>
	<idx><h>graph</h><h>breadth-first</h><h>search</h></idx>
	<p>
	To create a tree <m>T</m> that is a subgraph of a graph <m>G</m> wherein the <em>shortest</em> path in <m>G</m> from <m>v</m> to <m>v'</m> is evident,
	begin with <m>T</m> containing the single vertex <m>v</m> and no edges.
	<ol>
		<li xml:id="algorithm-trees-breadth-first-search-adjoin-adjacent">
		<!-- \label{ALGO::breadth.first::adjoin.adjacent} -->
			For each vertex <m>x</m> in <m>T</m> added in the last application of this step
			(or, in the case of the first application of this step, for <m>x = v</m>),
			adjoin <em>all</em> vertices of <m>G</m> that are adjacent to <m>x</m> and not already in <m>T</m>,
			along with a single edge between each such vertex and <m>x</m>.
			If at least one vertex has been adjoined to <m>T</m> in this step, proceed to
			<xref ref="algorithm-trees-breadth-first-search-stop-or-go" text="local">Step</xref>.
			Otherwise, stop <mdash /> there is no path from <m>v</m> to <m>v'</m> in <m>G</m>.
		</li>
		<li xml:id="algorithm-trees-breadth-first-search-stop-or-go">
			If <m>v'</m> was one of the vertices adjoined in
			<xref ref="algorithm-trees-breadth-first-search-adjoin-adjacent" text="local">Step</xref>,
			stop <mdash /> a path from <m>v</m> to <m>v'</m> exists and is now contained in <m>T</m>.
			Otherwise, return to
			<xref ref="algorithm-trees-breadth-first-search-adjoin-adjacent" text="local">Step</xref>.
		</li>
	</ol>
	</p>
</algorithm>

<example xml:id="example-trees-breadth-first-search">
	<title>Carrying out a breadth-first search</title>
	<p>
	Below is the result of the breadth-first algorithm,
	carried out to find a path from <m>1</m> to <m>9</m> in the graph
	in <xref ref="figure-trees-depth-first-example" />
	from <xref ref="example-trees-depth-first-search" />.
	</p>
	<figure xml:id="figure-trees-breadth-first-result">
		<caption>The result of a breadth-first search.</caption>
		<image xml:id="image-trees-breadth-first-results" width="64.7%">
			<description>The result tree of a breadth-first search.</description>
			<latex-image><xi:include href="trees.d/breadth-first-result.tex" parse="text" /></latex-image>
		</image>
	</figure>
</example>

</section>

<section xml:id="section-trees-spanning">
<title>Spanning trees</title>

<p><dl width="narrow">
	<li>
		<title>spanning subgraph</title>
		<idx><h>spanning</h><h>subgraph</h></idx>
		<idx><h>subgraph</h><h>spanning</h></idx>
		<p> a subgraph that contains <em>all</em> the vertices of the parent graph </p>
	</li>
	<li>
		<title>spanning tree</title>
		<idx><h>spanning</h><h>tree</h></idx>
		<idx><h>tree</h><h>spanning</h></idx>
		<p> a spanning subgraph that is a tree </p>
	</li>
</dl></p>

<example>
	<title>Spanning trees for the complete graph <m>K_4</m></title>
	<p> Here is the complete graph with four vertices. </p>
	<image xml:id="image-trees-K4" width="10.5%">
		<description>The complete graph with four vertices.</description>
		<latex-image><xi:include href="trees.d/K4.tex" parse="text" /></latex-image>
	</image>
	<p> And here are ten different spanning trees for <m>K_4</m>. </p>
	<image xml:id="image-trees-K4-spanning" width="77.3%">
		<description>Ten spanning trees for the complete graph with four vertices.</description>
		<latex-image><xi:include href="trees.d/K4-spanning.tex" parse="text" /></latex-image>
	</image>
</example>

<p>
If we carry out either of the depth-first or breadth-first search algorithms,
but aren't looking for a path between specific vertices, the end result will be a spanning tree for the original graph.
<dl width="narrow">
	<li>
		<title>depth-first spanning tree</title>
		<idx><h>depth-first</h><h>spanning tree</h></idx>
		<idx><h>graph</h><h>depth-first</h><h>spanning tree</h></idx>
		<p>
		the result of performing the depth-first search algorithm on a graph,
		continuing until all vertices in the original graph appear in the search tree
		</p>
	</li>
	<li>
		<title>breadth-first spanning tree</title>
		<idx><h>breadth-first</h><h>spanning tree</h></idx>
		<idx><h>graph</h><h>breadth-first</h><h>spanning tree</h></idx>
		<p>
		the result of performing the breadth-first search algorithm on a graph,
		continuing until all vertices in the original graph appear in the search tree
		</p>
	</li>
</dl>
</p>

<example>
	<title>Depth-first and breadth-first spanning trees</title>
	<p>
	<xref ref="figure-trees-depth-breadth-spanning" /> contains depth-first and breadth-first spanning trees for the graph
	in <xref ref="figure-trees-depth-first-example" />,
	our source of examples
	for depth-first search (<xref ref="example-trees-depth-first-search" />)
	and breadth-first search (<xref ref="example-trees-breadth-first-search" />).
	</p>
	<figure xml:id="figure-trees-depth-breadth-spanning">
		<caption>Examples of depth- and breadth-first spanning trees.</caption>
		<sbsgroup> <!-- TODO sbsgroup can also take widths... -->
			<sidebyside width="79.7%"><figure>
				<caption>Depth-first spanning tree for the graph in <xref ref="figure-trees-depth-first-example" />.</caption>
				<image xml:id="image-trees-depth-spanning">
					<description>A depth-first spanning tree.</description>
					<latex-image><xi:include href="trees.d/depth-spanning.tex" parse="text" /></latex-image>
				</image>
			</figure></sidebyside>
			<sidebyside width="64.7%"><figure>
				<caption>Breadth-first spanning tree for the graph in <xref ref="figure-trees-depth-first-example" />.</caption>
				<image xml:id="image-trees-breadth-spanning">
					<description>A breadth-first spanning tree.</description>
					<latex-image><xi:include href="trees.d/breadth-spanning.tex" parse="text" /></latex-image>
				</image>
			</figure></sidebyside>
		</sbsgroup>
	</figure>
</example>

</section>

<section xml:id="section-trees-binary-search">
<title>Binary searches</title>

<p><dl width="narrow">
	<li>
		<title>binary search tree</title>
		<idx><h>tree</h><h>binary search</h></idx>
		<idx><h>graph</h><h>binary search tree</h></idx>
		<p> a tree in which every node has degree <m>1</m> or <m>3</m>, except for a single node of degree <m>2</m> </p>
	</li>
	<li>
		<title>initial node</title>
		<idx>initial node (in a binary search tree)</idx>
		<idx><h>node</h><h>initial (in a binary search tree)</h></idx>
		<idx><h>vertex</h><h>initial (in a binary search tree)</h></idx>
		<p> the unique node of degree <m>2</m> in a binary search tree </p>
	</li>
	<li>
		<title>terminal node</title>
		<idx>terminal node (in a binary search tree)</idx>
		<idx><h>node</h><h>terminal (in a binary search tree)</h></idx>
		<idx><h>vertex</h><h>terminal (in a binary search tree)</h></idx>
		<p> a node of degree <m>1</m> in a binary search tree </p>
	</li>
	<li>
		<title>binary search</title>
		<idx><h>binary</h><h>search</h></idx>
		<p> the construction of a binary search tree through a series of <q>either-or</q> decisions </p>
	</li>
</dl></p>

<problem> <!-- worked example -->
	<statement><p> Estimate the root of <m>f(x) = 4x^3  + 6x^2  + 3x - 1</m> that lies in <m>(0,1)</m> to <m>2</m> decimal places. </p></statement>
	<solution>
		<p>
		The Intermediate Value Theorem from first-year calculus says that if <m>f</m> is continuous on the closed interval <m>[a,b]</m> and <m>f(a),f(b)</m> are nonzero and opposite signs,
		then <m>f</m> has a root in the open interval <m>(a,b)</m>.
		We have <m>f(0) = -1 \lt 0</m> and <m>f(1) = 12 \gt 0</m>,
		so there is indeed a root in <m>(0,1)</m>.
		The graph in <xref ref="figure-trees-binary-search-example" /> was obtained by performing a binary search by splitting into subintervals.
		</p>
		<figure xml:id="figure-trees-binary-search-example">
			<caption>A binary search tree search for the root of a polynomial.</caption>
			<image xml:id="image-trees-binary-search" width="90.5%">
				<description>An example binary search tree.</description>
				<latex-image><xi:include href="trees.d/binary-search.tex" parse="text" /></latex-image>
			</image>
		</figure>
		<p>
		Since <m>f(0.225) \gt 0</m>, the root must be in the subinterval <m>(0.22,0.225)</m>.
		This tells us to round down to <m>0.22</m> instead of rounding up to <m>0.23</m>,
		so we conclude that the root is approximately <m>0.22</m>.
		</p>
	</solution>
</problem>

</section>

